<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:medium;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Death and Glory</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Drundam stirred in his grave, his dark ashy handes broke from the freshly placed dirt above him. He slept in that shallow grave every night; it offered the best protection from outsiders. <br>
<br>
His kind had adapted quite well to breathing the small air pockets beneath the dirt, as this was necessary at the depths their colonies where built. However he was an outcast amongst the drow. He had no place in their halls of misery.<br>
<br>
As he climbed from his bed of soft dirt he adjusted his leather pants and brushed the dirt off him. The moon was full, it always seemed full here probably magic of some kind. That gloomy moon, and clear sky reflected off his ashy skin reflecting tints of blue. He seemed to have an almost visible aura.<br>
<br>
Drunam heard the howling in the distance, he hoped tonight wouldn't plague him with night crawlers again. Night crawlers always angered him, long centipede creatures whom spit acid with an exoskeleton that could handle most modern weapons, and their hollow white eyes made a solo drow shiver.<br>
<br>
The howling seemed to get closer he looked about the grave for the rest of his gear. He uncovered a backpack and short sword. The short swords blade shimmered radiant silver, he had stolen it from the corpse in the cemetery just over the hillside.<br>
<br>
He looked in the direction of the howling trying to keep his composure. &quot;Eioi bair!&quot; He uttered a common curse amongst his family. It roughly translated to damn light bringers a term used to describe his Fae cousins who enjoyed the sun.<br>
<br>
It was not a Fae that made the howling, as he could see the creatures outline now. It was a spectre of sorts, probably the dead man wanting his sword back. &quot;Wois Wius&quot; he shouted waving his sword to the left and touching the earth. Quickly a barrier rose between him and the ghost. &quot;Not toneght&quot; he spoke in broken common he had learned from a passing caravan. <br>
<br>
The spectre howled and slammed against the barrier, it's magical properties held the dead creature tightly in a magical cage. Drundam slung the backpack over his arms and carried his short sword in his left hand. He'd buy a sheath for it next time the caravan of tinker gnomes passed through.<br>
<br>
He ran quickly leaving the spectre behind, he was not like most drow and fled from battles he wasn't positive he'd win. That was why he was an outcast, he was pitted against a half-troll in his last colony and fled because no matter how many times he de-limbed the creature it continued to attack him.<br>
<br>
He barely escaped the pit's smooth granite walls just to be bombarded by clubs and curses from the crowd. He was then disowned from the Halls of his homeland. Sent to live above ground. Drundam would regain his place amongst his people, he would see to this, how he was not sure, but death brought glory in many forms.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Drundam stumbled upon a large canister following head first into the dirt. Frustrated he inspected the device it was a bomb of some kind. It looked active so he backed away. He hated the light barer they always deposited unused explosives in his land. Drundam dreamed of having the technology they wielded to return their devil contraptions to disrupt their society, and kill their families.<br>
<br>
He knew they would never understand, the lighter barers hated his people it was a trend nobody from Teir'Dal could escape. &quot;Eoioi Bair!&quot; he shouted into the sky. To loud this time as the ground around him rumbled.<br>
<br>
The dirt shifted and he lost his footing falling on his backside. He quickly scrambled to higher ground gripping tightly to a withered and gnarled tree. It was amazing they grew in such a harsh land but at this time was happy they did. The ground shifted and broke as a large creature stepped above the ground. It's hands alone where larger then his waist, it looked as if it had a large shell on it's back. It's skin was a deep brown and looked like that of a crab but it opened it's mouth letting out a sound that resonated knocking the tree and flinging himself against the hill.<br>
<br>
It stepped forward it's foot landing directly on the canister, the creatures weight which from first glance was more then an elephant set off the device. The device rippted through the creatures leg throwing shrapnel in all directions. A shard lodged itself in Drumdam's arm causing him to yell.<br>
<br>
The creature fell face first several meters from Drumdam green fluid leaked from it's now deformed limb but this did not stop the monster. It crawled forward grasping around Drumdam who was unable to escape despite all of his efforts. He hacked at the creatures arms but it did nothing but scratch what now looked like brown paint.<br>
<br>
The ground seem to spread beneath the two of them and he found himself being scratched by the dirt surface as he was pulled into the sub levels of this world. He tried to keep conscious but this effort alone was to much as he hit his head on stray rocks as the earth split and reformed around them.<br>
<br>
He woke in an empty cavern. Around him was one man and a trial of green liquid that lead to another room. Small creatures no more then a foot high where busy cleaning the surface of the black quartz floor.<br>
<br>
&quot;Welcome&quot; said the stranger in perfect common. &quot;My golem was sent to retrieve you and it did. It seems you have damaged it, I'd like to know how? As I have monitored you in the past and did not think your magic was of that caliber.&quot; <br>
<br>
Drundam's common was slow and broken. &quot;it wus nat mei it wus Eioi bair technulagy&quot; The man seemed to be patient and let Drundam complete his sentence. His face was quick to nod with understanding. <br>
<br>
&quot;Very well, we have much to discuss. I am planning something grand, and I need your assistance.&quot; He realized he spoke to quickly for the Drundam no matter they had many months of planning, he would teach Drundam to speak eloquent common. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Jarasmine Dranton Lamehstun was the name of Drundams captor. It was an interesting experience being captive because in these halls he had more feedom then he ever experienced. Nobody was trying to eat him, ostracize him or harm him. <br>
<br>
Jarasmine Dranton Lamehstun was a very cordial wizard who specialized in Golem creation. He employed the services of many small creatures who he thought at first glance where imps. Jarasmine corrected him, these where highly skilled worker golems made from the flesh of dwarves and the parts of stray waste canisters. He also housed a large mind flayer colony. How he kept them under control was a mystery, but they fed on the mental energy of any creature stupid enough to wander into their colony.<br>
<br>
The bodies where not of much use to the mind flayers, so they where given freely minus a few stray pieces for mind flayer trinkets to Jarasmine for his golem work. How he had never heard of this man Drundam did not know, as he seemed to have a rather efficient industry of golem creation, wizard training, and the first semi-civilized mind flayer colony he met.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am a man of exploration of the body and mind. I have been trying to bring Teir'Dal from its state of chaos into the force so mighty that the other provinces will be forced to offer us respect.&quot; This was the first time his calm demeanor broke, and it only broke in his eyes where Drundam could see the flash of destructive force resonate inside the mans dark blue eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Our goals are common, you have become an outcast and you want to be home against amongst your kind, but in order to do this, you must be educated, trained and made a fierce warrior mage to climb the ranks of their hierarchy to the TOP.&quot; The man spoke blasphemy all drow knew a male could never lead the female driven society.<br>
<br>
&quot;I can feel your thoughts Drundam and it is possible and I have the technology to make it happen. We can harness your fledgling skill into a fierce weapon, and by placing you at the head of your drow colony we will be one step further to uniting Teir'Dal and continue where the Dragon of the Void left off.&quot; Jarasmine's voice was full of passion and strength.<br>
<br>
Dundam's silence was consent and the pact was made. The first months Drundam sat in a library with a nymph who's body was beautiful naked, and exposed she too was a creation. She had been enslaved by the drow as a concubine slave, but the caravan owner drifted to deep, and the entire caravan learned the hard way what mind flayers where capable of doing.<br>
<br>
She now had the mind of a scholar and genius intelligence imposed on her reconstructed mind by Jarasmine. She would be Dundam's instructor and she would teach him languages many, many languages. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Two months passed and Drundam quickly learned English, he was even instructed on the rest of his native tongue, deep dwarf, and even that of the frail light barers. His learning rate was increased by a cocktail of drinks given to him by Jarasmine to speed him along. Drundam left the halls of the library leaving the nymph alone again to ponder her creation.<br>
<br>
Walking towards him was Jarasmine down the curved confined path that connected the intricate maze Drundam quickly memorized as home. &quot;So you are ready to learn the higher arts?&quot; Jarasmine knew already Drundam was a fairly decent warrior, and a mage of respectable skill. This was the reason he chose him, but by higher arts he meant skills that would surpass any known drow magician.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm ready for more answers.&quot; Drundam spoke clearly his voice resonating down the hall in a soft baritone. He cold feel the magic in him flow through his new voice and new the cocktails did more then just increase intelligence. &quot;I want answers.&quot; He said again the voice resonating passed Jarasmine who too noticed the subtle command in the voice that pulled at his mind.<br>
<br>
Jarasmine smiled placed his arm around Drundam pleased. He had monitored his progress off and on but overall Jarasmine had been monitoring and preparing for his ultimate goal of uniting Teir'Dal which needed more then just Drundam skills. There where many races and many colonies Drundam was one of many projects of Jarasmine.<br>
<br>
&quot;Walk with me, Drundam I will answer what you ask.&quot; He lead Drundam to an open stadium of sorts that over looked the mind flayer colony. They stood hundreds of feet above the quick footed creatures who's minds could feel the presence of the spies above them.<br>
<br>
&quot;How did you get them under your control?&quot; Asked drundam knowing that control was a strong word, almost insulting to mind flayers.<br>
<br>
&quot;They are not under my control Drundam. They are under my protection. You see I have lived in Menelmacar for many years hidden from the eyes of the leaders until recently. With the immigration of Archetype the mind flayers grew anxious, and feared for their lives, as Archetype is not one to have psion competition, so they grew scared as a few of their less careful brethren spied on the mad man of yellows home. They lost their mind.. painted their rooms yellow.. and could not function.. they starved to death inside their painted homes.&quot; Jarasmine continued to explain.<br>
<br>
&quot;So they fled because Archetype nightly began purging the depths of Teir'Dal of the competition he now had. There only protection was short lasted as the Dragon of the Void rallied them and broke away from Sirithil but this did not last long as Teir'Dal was once again re-united with Menelmacar under now.. Archetypes rule.&quot; Drundam listened intently to Jarasmines words.<br>
<br>
&quot;They stumbled upon my layer and found that Archetype could not find them here. The magical barrier I have around this section of Teir'Dal prevented his scrying eyes, and that of his brethren KinTCR and Pathfollower from viewing us. Archetype has been busy with the internal workings of Menelmacar but they doubt he has forgotten of their presence, so they remain here, as business partners so to speak. They will help us free Teir'Dal Drundam so long as we respect their right to live and feed just as we have a right to live and feed.&quot; Jarasmine looked away from the colony and looked at Drundam that insanity again flashed in Jarasmines dark blue eyes like miniature lightning bolts of psychotic splendor. <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm ready to learn the higher arts.&quot; Drundam spoke not as confident as before he asked the question. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Drundam spent an hour each day sitting in a room with a mind flayer. No conversation took place, just the presence of the other was enough to train someones will power. This continued along with his other magical training. This would make him immune to mind control freeing him from any attempt that could be made by Archetype to stop the unification of Teir'Dal. However he would be forced to train long and hard as Jarasmine cautioned him that the Dragon who speaks through the void would lash out if they where not careful.<br>
